The 183rd New York State Legislature, a body composed of the [New York State Senate](/New_York_State_Senate) and the [New York State Assembly](/New_York_State_Assembly), convened from January 3, 1979, through December 31, 1980. This period marked the latter half of [Hugh Carey](/Hugh_Carey)'s tenure as [Governor of New York](/Governor_of_New_York), with legislative proceedings primarily centered in the [New York State Capitol](/New_York_State_Capitol) in [Albany](/Albany,_New_York).

### Background

The framework for this legislative session was established by the [New York Constitution](/New_York_Constitution) of 1938, further shaped by the U.S. Supreme Court's mandate to adhere to the [One man, one vote](/One_man,_one_vote) principle. This principle necessitated reapportionment, which had been undertaken in 1971 and subsequently amended in 1974 by the legislature itself. The outcome was a bicameral structure comprising 60 Senators and 150 Assembly members, each elected to two-year terms representing single-seat districts. These districts were designed to contain roughly equivalent populations, with contiguous boundaries and no strict adherence to county lines.

Within the state's political landscape, two dominant parties vied for influence: the [Republican Party](/Republican_Party_(United_States)) and the [Democratic Party](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)). Beyond these major players, several other parties fielded candidates, including the [Conservative Party](/Conservative_Party_of_New_York_State), the [Right to Life Party](/New_York_State_Right_to_Life_Party), the [Liberal Party](/Liberal_Party_of_New_York), the [Libertarian Party](/Libertarian_Party_(United_States)), the [Socialist Workers Party](/Socialist_Workers_Party_(United_States)), the [Communist Party](/Communist_Party_USA), and the [Labor Party](/U.S._Labor_Party). Their presence, while often smaller in scale, added nuance to the electoral dynamics.

### Elections

The electoral landscape leading into the 183rd session was significantly shaped by the [1978 New York state election](/1978_New_York_gubernatorial_election), held on November 7. This election saw the re-election of Governor [Hugh Carey](/Hugh_Carey), a Democrat, and the ascent of Secretary of State [Mario Cuomo](/Mario_Cuomo) to the position of Lieutenant Governor, also a Democrat. The contests for the other two statewide offices resulted in a Republican victory for Comptroller and a Democratic win for Attorney General. The voting patterns for Governor offered a snapshot of the prevailing political sentiment, with Democrats garnering approximately 2,306,000 votes, Republicans 1,913,000, Conservatives 243,000, Right to Life 130,000, Liberals 123,000, Libertarians 19,000, Socialist Workers 13,000, Communists 11,000, and the Labor Party 9,000.

The legislature saw a notable increase in female representation. Seven of the ten women who served in the previous legislative session were re-elected. These included State Senators [Olga A. Méndez](/Olga_A._M%C3%A9ndez) (Dem.) from [East Harlem](/East_Harlem) and [Linda Winikow](/Linda_Winikow) (Dem.) from [Spring Valley, New York](/Spring_Valley,_New_York). In the Assembly, re-elected members were [Elizabeth Connelly](/Elizabeth_Connelly) (Dem.) of [Staten Island](/Staten_Island), [Pinny Cooke](/Pinny_Cooke) (Rep.) of [Rochester, New York](/Rochester,_New_York), [Estella B. Diggs](/Estella_B._Diggs) (Dem.) of [the Bronx](/The_Bronx), and [Gerdi E. Lipschutz](/Gerdi_E._Lipschutz) (Dem.) of [Queens](/Queens). Additionally, Assemblywoman [Mary B. Goodhue](/Mary_B._Goodhue), a lawyer from [Mount Kisco, New York](/Mount_Kisco,_New_York), transitioned to the state Senate. [Carol Berman](/Carol_Berman) (Dem.) of [Lawrence, Nassau County, New York](/Lawrence,_Nassau_County,_New_York) also secured a seat in the state Senate. The Assembly gained further female representation with the election of [Rhoda S. Jacobs](/Rhoda_S._Jacobs) (Dem.) from [Brooklyn](/Brooklyn); [Joan B. Hague](/Joan_B._Hague) (Rep.) from [Glens Falls, New York](/Glens_Falls,_New_York); [May W. Newburger](/May_W._Newburger) (Dem.) from [Great Neck, New York](/Great_Neck,_New_York); [Toni Rettaliata](/Toni_Rettaliata) (Rep.) from [Huntington, New York](/Huntington,_New_York); and [Florence M. Sullivan](/Florence_M._Sullivan) (Rep.), also a lawyer from [Brooklyn](/Brooklyn). Consequently, the 183rd Legislature boasted 13 women members, exceeding the previous record of 11 set during the [181st New York State Legislature](/181st_New_York_State_Legislature) (1976).

The subsequent [1979 New York state election](/1978_New_York_gubernatorial_election), held on November 6, 1979, did not feature elections for any statewide offices, nor were there any legislative vacancies to fill.

### Sessions

The legislative year commenced with the first regular session, designated as the 202nd, which opened at the State Capitol in [Albany, New York](/Albany,_New_York) on January 3, 1979. This session saw the election of [Stanley Fink](/Stanley_Fink) (Dem.) as [Speaker](/Speaker_of_the_New_York_State_Assembly) of the Assembly. Simultaneously, [Warren M. Anderson](/Warren_M._Anderson) (Rep.) was re-elected as the temporary president of the state Senate. The session proceeded until June 17, 1979, when it recessed indefinitely.

Intermittently throughout October and November 1979, the legislature reconvened to address matters concerning energy policy. These sessions were notably marked by legislative action on fuel taxes and aid for heating, with the Assembly overriding two of Governor Carey's vetoes on heating aid bills, and the Senate also overriding two such vetoes.

The second regular session, the 203rd, commenced on January 9, 1980, again at the State Capitol in Albany. Governor Carey used this opening to call for fiscal restraint and increased federal support for the state. This session continued until its indefinite recess on June 15, 1980.

A special session was subsequently convened at the State Capitol in Albany, running from November 19 to November 23, 1980. This extraordinary gathering was specifically called by Governor Carey to deliberate on legislation pertaining to banking, the state budget, and housing initiatives within New York City.

